<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910729-0099</DOCNO><DOCID>910729-0099.</DOCID><HL>   Two Big Thrifts Sold   By Resolution Trust   In Georgia, Arkansas</HL><DATE>07/29/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12</SO><CO>   GMFD MTRC</CO><MS>FINANCIAL (FIN)</MS><IN>CENTRAL U.S. BANKS (BAC)ALL REGIONAL BANKS (BAR)ALL BANKS, BANKING NEWS AND ISSUES (BNK)SAVINGS AND LOANS, THRIFTS (SAL)TENDER OFFERS, MERGERS, ACQUISITIONS (TNM)</IN><NS>ACQUISITIONS andamp; MERGERS, TAKEOVERS, BOARD BATTLES (TNM)</NS><GV>FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (FDL)</GV><RE>ARKANSAS (AR)GEORGIA (GA)ILLINOIS (IL)MASSACHUSETTS (MA)MISSOURI (MO)NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   WASHINGTON -- The Resolution Trust Corp. said it soldlarge savings-and-loan institutions in Georgia and Arkansas.   The 37 offices of Fulton Federal Savings Association,Atlanta, were sold to eight institutions and will reopentoday. In the largest part of the sale, South Trust Bank,Atlanta, acquired $768.8 million of deposits from FultonFederal's 22 Atlanta area branches.</LP><TEXT>   Fulton Federal had $1.36 billion in assets and totalliabilities of $1.43 billion. The eight purchasers will buy$416.1 million of the assets, while the RTC will advance them$808.3 million and retain about $940 million of FultonFederal's assets. The RTC will recover some money through thesale of assets, and expects the transaction to cost thegovernment $314 million.   Meanwhile, First Savings of Arkansas, Little Rock, wassold to 22 financial institutions, and 30 of its 32 officeswill reopen today. First Savings had total assets of $878.7million, and about $1.2 billion of liabilities. The acquiringinstitutions will assume all deposits, about $1 billion.   The RTC will advance $948 million to the purchasers andretain about $830.7 million of First Savings's assets. Theagency puts the ultimate cost of the transaction at $863.4million.   In other actions, the RTC sold Sentry Savings Bank,Hyannis, Mass., to New Bedford Institution for Savings, NewBedford, Mass., which will assume all insured deposits andsecured liabilities totaling $462.9 million. The RTC saidthis transaction ultimately would cost the government $166.9million.   The RTC also sold Germania Bank, Alton, Ill., toMercantile Bank of St. Louis, St. Louis. Mercantile Bank willassume all insured deposits, which total $308 million. TheRTC put the cost of this transaction at $125 million.</TEXT></DOC>